<DOCNO> AP880912-0002 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
union leaders ended britains 13day mail strike 
monday but home and international service will remain disrupted 
for two weeks as workers wade through a backlog of 150 million 
letters and packages officials said 
the national executive board of the union of communication 
workers which represents 180000 post office employees announced 
its support monday for a pact to end the walkout said spokesman 
allen slater 
the objective by both sides should be to return to work by 
thursday slater said 
the 100000 striking workers will iron out returntowork 
details with managers at local post offices he said 
this has been an extremely damaging dispute for our 
customers said bill cockburn managing director of royal mail 
letters the letters and parcels division of the post office 
there is a mountain of mail and there will be an allout effort 
to move it 
union secretarygeneral alan tuffin said local union chiefs will 
forge their own deals on overtime and the use of temporary workers 
we are going to try to get this industry back on its feet with 
the cooperation of the workforce he said in a tv news broadcast 
on channel four 
post office leaders agreed to a backtowork plan last thursday 
but tuffin said he wanted no misunderstanding and sent his 
negotiators back to the table over the weekend 
mondays agreement also establishes a framework for further 
discussions on the strikes central issue of regional pay 
supplements 
post office spokeswoman melanie corfield said local managers may 
press returning strikers to accept a number of temporary employees 
to cope with the christmaslike volume of mail 
international mail firstclass letters and parcels will receive 
priority as the backlog is cleared said ms corfield 
public mailboxes which have been sealed throughout the dispute 
will reopen only when we can guarantee people normal service 
again she said 
the post office wishes to pay bonuses to new workers in london 
and southeast england where the cost of living is high and 
retaining workers proves difficult 
the union demanded that the bonuses be paid across the country 
or not all and began a 24hour work stoppage aug 31 that burgeoned 
into a series of crippling wildcat strikes 
tuffin said a deal could be reached over the pay issue within 
six weeks 
about half of britains 1500 local post offices closed down 
during the strike and of the 82 major sorting centers only one in 
belfast northern ireland was open for business before the 
agreement was announced monday said ms corfield 
</TEXT>
