a the bush administration will be an open one that doesnt 
mean every staff member will be authorized to serve as an 
administration spokesman or interpreter of events and policies the 
best interests of the government media and public arent observed 
by the confusion and misinformation that usually results from that 
kind of policy 
not in every instance but in most if something cant be said on 
the record its probably better left unsaid 
q what would be your policy on allowing media coverage of 
military actions a la grenada do you support the pool approach 
worked out and used in the persian gulf exercises or do you 
believe reporters and photographers ought to have even freer access 
to military operations 
a certainly the public has a right to know the details of 
military operations in an appropriate time frame and in a way that 
does not risk national security the current relationship between 
the military and the press is workable and i support it but that 
safety of the troops and the success of the mission must be 
paramount and i will risk neither 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
freedom of information for the past eight years the 
reaganbush administration has waged an assault on the freedom of 
information act foia with every weapon in its arsenal executive 
orders budget cuts fee guidelines and legislative proposals 
their objective is clear to gut a statute whose fundamental 
premise is that american citizens have the right to know about the 
activities of their own government 
the current administration claims that complying with the foia 
is too timeconsuming too expensive and too bothersome these are 
excuses for government secrecy and they could serve as a cloak for 
incompetence mismanagement illegality or corruption 
as president i will implement the foia in the spirit which 
congress intended from vietnam to watergate to irancontra we 
americans have learned what happens when government operates in 
secrecy accountable to no one a dukakis administration will treat 
requesters of information as clients not as burdens for only in 
an atmosphere of the fullest possible disclosure can the american 
people retain confidence in their government 
relations with the press throughout my public career ive 
believed in a free press and my record shows ive practiced that 
belief as governor for nearly 10 years i have been accessible to 
state house reporters several times a week i enjoy the spirited 
give and take of news conferences and the vigorous exchange of an 
interview more important i understand and appreciate the role of 
the news media in a free society as laid out two centuries ago in 
the bill of rights to the constitution 
as president i would hope to continue this pattern of 
accessibility to the white house press corps giving them and me 
the opportunity to utilize our first amendment freedoms 
