<TEXT>
a preliminary review by the agriculture 
department of this summers barge traffic on droughtreduced rivers 
shows some of the huge problems that have plagued the movement of 
grain from inland farm points into export shipping channels 
in midjune low water levels on the lower mississippi and ohio 
rivers began to stall barges at choke points for more than a day 
by the end of the month stoppages were a regular occurrence 
reduced load size smaller tows and lengthened transit times 
have dropped the capacity of the mississippi river system by at 
least 50 percent the report said difficult navigation and 
increased travel time add to costs especially for fuel and labor 
which normally account for about 35 percent of total operating 
costs 
overall according to a recent industry study barge operators 
could lose as much as 200 million this year 
the smaller river flow forced gyrations in barge rates the 
report said even before the droughts full effect rates were 
going higher because of greater demand in the first five months 
they averaged nearly a fourth more than in the same januarymay 
period of 1987 
in the first two weeks of june barge rates jumped 4 percent 
from the end of may by the end of june rates had nearly tripled 
this increase was shortlived the report said in the 
first week of july rates fell to about 125 percent above the end 
of may and by months end had returned to predrought levels 
by the first week of august rates from peoria ill to export 
points at new orleans la averaged 685 per ton up 12 percent 
from a year earlier 
the decline in rates after the first week of july resulted 
from a sharp reduction in demand for barge service the report 
said as export volume shrank and producers held stocks in 
anticipation of higher prices shipments of grain and soybeans in 
june fell 16 percent from may and in july dropped 37 percent from 
may 
according to the new outlook report by the departments economic 
research service the higher transportation costs and reduced 
capacity sharply boosted prices of corn delivered by barge to 
louisianas gulf ports 
between june 17 and june 23 corn prices rose from 331 to 
332 per bushel to a range of 363 to 366 per bushel the 
report said 
these ports account for about 50 percent of us grain exports 
and receive 70 percent of the grain chiefly corn by barge the 
report said similar price increases are anticipated in the 
poultry producing areas of the southeast barges normally carry 
about a third of the grain shipped to these states 
trucks are not an alternative to barges for moving grain the 
report said a fully loaded barge holds 1500 tons of grain or 
about 35 truck loads a milelong truck convoy bumpertobumper 
would replace fewer than 2 barges 
one day 1760 barges were stacked above greenville miss 
287 miles from new orleans the report said grain in these 
barges would have filled a line of trucks 755 miles long 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
a forecast by the agriculture department that 
the cash receipts of farmers are likely to increase this year 
despite huge production losses due to drought has put economists to 
work explaining why 
cash receipts or the gross from sales of crops and livestock 
are expected to rise 5 billion to 9 billion this year from 1987 
says the departments economic research service in 1980 another 
drought year farm cash receipts climbed nearly 8 billion 
since droughts have an impact on production why dont cash 
receipts decline 
one reason is that the prices of droughtaffected commodities 
tend to increase more than production falls raising the total 
value of the crop the agency says in a new outlook report 
another reason is that marketing does not drop as much as 
production because stocks inventories are sold to make up the 
harvest shortfall 
the economists say the demand for farm commodities is inelastic 
meaning that a 1 percent decline in production for example leads 
to a price increase greater than 1 percent 
some farmers may benefit from the higher prices those in 
areas with adequate rainfall those who irrigate and those with 
large unsold stocks of previous years crops the report said 
however higher cash receipts nationally do not imply that all 
farmers are better off because of the drought 
the report added many farmers will suffer large declines in 
cash receipts if their individual production falls by much more 
than prices rise farmers in droughtstricken areas without large 
stocks of unsold crops from previous years have little to fall back 
on 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
honey bees are famous for pollinating crops 
but an agriculture department scientist says the bees dont work 
hard enough when it comes to hybrid cotton plants 
gerald m loper a plant physiologist at the carl hayden bee 
research center tucson ariz said theres something about cotton 
pollen that bees dont like 
they will spend 20 minutes meticulously combing the pollen off 
their bodies before returning to their hives he said and thats 
time lost from their job of pollinating cotton plants 
bees are needed to pollinate hybrid strains of cotton by 
carrying pollen from male to female plants which produce the 
hybrid seed regular cotton does its own pollinating without the 
help of bees 
the hybrid strains have a potential for boosting cotton yields 
by as much as 25 percent and producing long fiber for specialty 
markets loper said in a recent report if only the bees would work 
harder 
india and mexico grow hybrid cotton but rely on hand labor for 
pollination to produce seeds labor costs and import restrictions 
on foreign cotton seed have put pressure on the honey bee to do the 
job in the united states loper said 
</TEXT>
