smoke from the forest fires in yellowstone national park has 
drifted as far as the east coast turning sunsets a fiery red and 
even affecting the weather 
the setting sun had a kind of an eerie appearance said 
allan morrison of the national weather service in chicago about 
1200 miles east of the fires the hazy smoke made the sun look 
like a big glowing red ball it was a very red color which 
made it spectacular in that regard 
the smoke was trapped in an upper atmospheric trough about 
15000 to 20000 feet up and was carried by wind over the great 
lakes toward the east coast and out to sea said meteorologist joe 
harrison of the weather service in new york city 
the thin layer of smoke passed over the new york area sunday 
dimming the sun to a reddishorange and lowering temperatures 
between 5 and 10 degrees harrison said 
the only effect were having is its interfering with the 
radiation of the sun said robert a armbrust an airquality 
engineer with the new york state department of environmental 
conservation 
boston still had a thin transparent layer of haze monday said 
weather service meteorologist tom emerson 
usually smoke from large fires is dispersed and is not 
noticeable so far away harrison said 
because the smoke was so high up the smell was not noticeable 
on the ground and it did not contribute to air pollution he added 
pilots reported seeing the smoke layer over chicago when they 
climbed to cruising altitudes of 30000 and 40000 feet but no 
visibility problems were reported 
however visibility was a problem closer to the fires in 
western south dakota about 400 miles east of the blazes 
visibility has been as low as half a mile and foresters warned 
that would hinder detection of local forest fires 
