<TEXT>
africa is facing huge debts lagging food 
production and a soaring infant mortality rate despite broad 
economic and social reforms un secretarygeneral javier perez de 
cuellar said monday 
the un chief speaking at the opening of a twoweek review of 
the un africa recovery program gave a grim prognosis for the 
continent 
among the signs of distress he cited 
infant and child mortality rates are rising and are projected 
to reach 50 million in the period 19852000 in every other world 
region infant and child mortality is rapidly decreasing 
by the year 2010 africas debt will be more than 280 percent 
of its total export income 
per capita income on the continent fell 2 percent in 1986 and 
22 percent in 1987 and today is lower than it was in 1980 
agricultural production improved by 38 percent in 1986 but 
only 11 percent in 1987 despite agricultural policy reforms 
perez de cuellars report marks the midway point of the 
19861990 africa recovery program the result of a special general 
assembly session in may 1986 the first such session to focus on 
one continent 
the program was aimed at helping reverse africas economic 
decline but external problems have blocked substantial progress 
perez de cuellar said 
he said three key problems are africas depressed export 
earnings the cost of repaying its debt and insufficient financing 
every day that passes the debt burden of african countries 
becomes even more excruciating said adebayo adedeji un 
undersecretarygeneral 
although africa paid almost 1 billion a year to the 
international monetary fund in loan costs in 1986 and 1987 
resources fell exports credit declined and loans from the private 
sector were minor the un chiefs report said 
africas debt burden has become one of the most important 
factors constraining recovery and development on the continent and 
unless urgent action is taken the situation will worse said 
perez de cuellar 
africas total external debt is estimated by the un economic 
commission for africa at 218 billion by the end of 1987 almost 
triple the continents export earnings 
a slump in commodity prices has further hurt africas economy 
particulary damaging are the sluggish markets for oil minerals 
cocoa coffee and tea 
these problems largely canceled out any gain that might have 
been produced by the courageous and commendable sacrifices of 
some african governments such as adopting steep currency 
devaluations cutting budget deficits and an turning over some 
public sector functions to the private sector 
in many countries such measures involve social costs and 
political risks perez de cuellar noted 
most african nations have embarked on economic restructuring 
programs about 30 percent of them with the backing of the imf and 
world bank 
most countries are giving greater priority to channeling 
resources to agriculture to improving incentives for farmers to 
making provision for food security and to combating drought and 
decertification the secretarygeneral said 
perez de cuellar urged african nations to continue these 
restructuring programs but cautioned them to ensure that the 
most vulnerable groups in society are protected from adverse 
consequences 
donor countries should show their support for these reforms by 
increasing their aid he said 
perez de cuellar called on industrialized nations to reduce 
their agricultural subsidies on products competing with african 
commodities 
african efforts to pursue and deepen the reform process cannot 
be sustained indefinitely in the face of an adverse external 
environment and without increased support from the international 
community the secretarygeneral said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

