<TEXT>
irans parliament approved 18 ministers 
monday in a vote of confidence for prime minister hussein musavis 
government but rejected three including revolutionary guards 
minister mohsen rafiqdoust tehran radio said 
the twoday debate exposed the deep divisions in the tehran 
hierarchy that had largely been masked by the need for unity during 
the 8yearold war with iraq 
the veto on rafiqdoust underscored the anger over disastrous 
battlefield defeats suffered by iran before it abruptly accepted a 
yearold united nationssponsored ceasefire july 18 these 
setbacks had been blamed on the revolutionary guards 
iran and iraq began observing a truce aug 20 and started 
unmediated peace talks in geneva five days later 
the parliamentary debate which musavi announced in july opened 
sunday amid a deepening rift between hardline revolutionaries 
demanding economic isolationism and tight state control of the 
economy and rivals such as house speaker hashemi rafsanjani who 
seek to open up oilrich iran in the postwar era 
several deputies attacked hardliner musavis economic policies 
while radical legislators loyal to the premier defended his 
administration 
tehran radio monitored in nicosia gave few details of mondays 
session 
but the radio said the 11 ministers of the 21member cabinet who 
were crossexamined by the 270member majlis or parliament 
included interior minister ali akbar mohtashemi oil minister 
alireza aqazadeh heavy industry minister behzad nabavi and 
rafiqdoust 
besides rafiqdoust education and training minister kazem akrami 
and minister of agriculture and rural development abbas zali also 
received a noconfidence vote 
musavi will have to choose three new ministers to replace them 
the fact that other close allies of musavi won the vote of 
confidence indicated that a headon clash between radicals and 
conservatives over irans postwar economic policy has been averted 
at least for now 
musavi prime minister for seven years warned sunday that a 
vote of no confidence in his cabinet would seriously hamper irans 
postwar recovery 
musavi 46 submitted his resignation to president ali khamenei 
on sept 5 saying he believed at least eight of his ministers 
faced noconfidence votes 
khamenei rejected the resignation and ayatollah ruhollah 
khomeini the 88yearold revolutionary patriarch publicly rebuked 
musavi for making the surprise move at such a critical juncture 
while iran was negotiating a peace settlement with iraq 
musavi retracted his resignation but complained of 
difficulties in the decisionmaking process in the executive 
an apparent sideswipe at his rivals khamenei and rafsanjani 
khomeinis intervention put off any major political crisis in 
iran but analysts believe the end of the war will bring profound 
changes in iran and that musavi could be among the political 
casualties 
musavi reportedly opposed a truce he opposes allowing foreign 
multinationals back into iran to help with the massive task of 
reconstruction rafsanjani and khamenei favor a more moderate 
course and ending irans selfimposed isolation 
khamenei on monday opened tehrans 14th international trade 
fair in which 36 countries were participating 
some like france were taking part for the first time since the 
1979 islamic revolution toppled the late prowestern shah mohammad 
reza pahlavi 
the official islamic republic news agency also monitored in 
cyprus said other foreign participants included the soviet union 
argentina australia switzerland west germany ireland sweden 
japan and south korea 
irna quoted commerce minister abdulhussein vahaji as stressing 
that iran welcomes foreign technological assistance for 
reconstruction projects and said iran now seeks to expand 
commercial links with the rest of the world 
some western analysts have estimated that irans postwar 
reconstruction could cost 40 billion 
</TEXT>
