mikhail s gorbachev in his first public 
appearance after a sixweek vacation ran into crowds complaining 
loudly about food shortages and living conditions monday in the 
siberian city of krasnoyarsk 
the evening television news program vremya led its evening 
program with a report on the kremlin leaders trip to the city 
about 2000 miles east of moscow 
gorbachev had been out of public view since july 30 when he met 
with foreign minister hansdietrich genscher of west germany 
soviet officials said he was on vacation 
gorbachev asked for support for his reform policies as residents 
of krasnoyarsk pressed close to him and complained about lack of 
hot water and long lines for meat sausage and other foods 
the clamor was in marked contrast to the usual orderly scenes of 
gorbachev visits on soviet tv many of the comments and complaints 
were inaudible 
the most important thing is that you believe in our politics 
and in the leadership that is still being formed its still being 
formed at the regional and provincial levels gorbachev said 
he told the residents he was not interested in blind faith but 
in reasoned trust for his policies and the people implementing them 
were on the right path comrades he said no need to get 
lost were on the right path 
the soviet leader blamed both local and national officials for 
failing to develop social services in krasnoyarsk and reiterated 
that he is committed to providing each soviet family with a 
separate apartment by the year 2000 
gorbachev arrived in krasnoyarsk on a special aeroflot plane and 
met with residents near the airport and again near the citys 
central square where he laid a wreath at a monument to soviet 
founder vladimir i lenin 
he defended his tolerance of greater debate and criticism in the 
soviet press and encouragement of cooperatives outside the 
staterun economy 
one woman complained that cooperatives owned by the people who 
run them rather than by the government charge too much for their 
services 
gorbachev agreed that cooperative prices are high but told the 
woman that as more coops are formed competition will drive prices 
down 
gorbachev has encouraged cooperatives to provide goods and 
services that are in short supply in the staterun economy 
a man complained that under his policy of glasnost or greater 
openness the staterun press is free to attack anyone by name 
whether they deserve it or not 
the soviet leader responded we need openness we need 
glasnost but it has to be according to our values according to 
socialism and according to people 
no indication emerged how long gorbachev would remain in 
krasnoyarsk the regional center for an area that takes in 
onetenth of the entire soviet union 
krasnoyarsk also is the site of a soviet radar station that the 
united states says is an obstacle to arms control negotiations 
gorbachev did not discuss the radar site in comments distributed by 
the tass news agency and shown on soviet television 
