<TEXT>
us and soviet observers came to 
this central asian city monday to prepare for the first soviet 
nuclear test monitored by american experts a step toward ratifying 
two longpending arms treaties 
arms negotiator c paul robinson who heads the american 
delegation said it had been a long journey but an even longer 
journey in the mind to reach the point at which the two 
superpowers are willing to share some of their most closely guarded 
technology in the interest of arms control 
robinson spoke before setting off by bus across the steppe to 
the soviet test ground 
an american team of up to 40 specialists has worked at the site 
since april drilling a hole 2100 feet into the earth to plant a 
measuring device the us government calls the most sensitive gauge 
of nuclear explosions 
a test blast to be detonated wednesday is similar to one 
exploded at the us test site on pahute mesa nev on aug 17 
the devices are being set off to allow each side use its own 
testing equipment and compare the results with those of the other 
side to determine the strength of the blast and the accuracy of the 
monitoring techniques 
the joint experiments are expected to lead to us senate 
ratification of two longdormant treaties limiting underground 
nuclear explosions to 150 kilotons still many times more powerful 
than the bomb that devasted hiroshima japan 
a kiloton is the equivalent of the explosion of 1000 tons of 
tnt 
those pacts the threshold nuclear test ban treaty of 1974 and 
a similar accord signed in 1976 to limit peaceful nuclear 
explosions were bypassed by president jimmy carter who pressed 
instead for a comprehensive ban on all nuclear testing 
his successor ronald reagan shelved the unratified documents 
claiming the soviets regularly violated their limits without 
permitting onsite verification 
the soviet union unsuccessfully sought for 18 months to cajole 
the united states into joining a soviet moratorium on all nuclear 
tests it abandoned the effort last february and agreed to go along 
with joint verification of tests as a step toward its goal of a 
total ban 
no one thought even a year ago that what is about to happen 
could happen robinson said monday he called the joint 
verification experiment a real triumph of confidencebuilding 
on both sides 
detailed results of last months test have not yet been 
released but us officials speaking on condition they not be 
identified have expressed considerable satisfaction with the 
results 
reports have surfaced that the us measuring gear which the 
united states contends is more accurate than soviet methods showed 
that the american test exceeded the 150kiloton limit 
but officials said monday they regarded that possibility as 
very very unlikely noting that even with its muchheralded 
accuracy the us measuring device can be 30 percent off 
</TEXT>
