<TEXT>
american companies are scrambling to 
make sure they are not shut out of the lucrative new market that 
will be formed in western europe in 1992 
thats when the 12 nations of the european economic community 
eec remove the many trade barriers separating them 
were living through a historic period in europe it is all 
happening you ignore it at your peril said eamonn bates 
european community affairs manager for the american chamber of 
commerce in brussels the eec headquarters 
every aspect of doing business in europe is going to change 
in response top us companies are opening special offices 
reviewing business strategies and hiring consultants to get ready 
for the next decade when the eec becomes a single market of 320 
million consumers 
american companies in europe are taking the issue very very 
seriously said walter di pretoro who recently assumed his post 
as senior vice president for eec affairs for honeywell 
many executives say the farreaching changes while spurring 
greater competition should lead to reduced costs and bigger sales 
youre going to operate in a much more difficult 
environment said antonio patron government affairs manager for 
hewlettpackard in geneva but if you play your cards right 
you will benefit substantially 
reagan administration officials though worry that the 
europeans might use their newfound togetherness to try to keep out 
us and other foreign competition 
alfred kingon the us ambassador to the eec said in an 
interview what im afraid of is that when the barriers come 
down the competition among themselves is going to be so great 
that there will be an instinctive protectionist push 
european officials might decide he said all right well open 
it up internally but well have to limit it externally 
they insist it wont happen he said i hope theyre 
right 
community officials dismiss concerns they will create a 
fortress europe in 1992 
these fears are totally unjustified willy de clercq the 
eecs top trade official said in a recent speech 
the idea of the europeanwide market is to reduce the barriers 
that keep goods services people and money from moving freely 
among the 12 eec countries belgium britain denmark france 
germany greece ireland italy luxembourg netherlands portugal 
and spain 
they would put simply become more like the united states where 
people and goods with some exceptions can travel freely from 
state to state 
the europeans have drawn up a list of 285 steps that need to be 
taken to remove physical technical and fiscal obstacles to unity 
their deadline for completing the task is the end of 1992 so far 
92 of the measures have been adopted 
the 1992 pace has quickened dramatically since february when 
european leaders agreed on measures to solve a longstanding 
dispute over the trading blocs budget with their money woes 
apparently out of the way officials have turned their attention to 
fashioning the single market 
many big us companies with strong european ties do not expect 
discriminatory moves against their operations but rather believe 
they stand to gain when the barriers are removed 
john wells external affairs manager at ibms office in paris 
cites such statements by eec chief executive jacques delors as one 
made in an interview with the international herald tribute of 
paris companies working inside the community will continue to be 
welcomed ibm conducts a share of its rampd research and 
development in europe for us ibm is a european company 
we feel zero threat said stephen telegdy director of 
government affairs for dow chemical in brussels we feel we stand 
to gain and have nothing to lose by the european integration 
dow estimates the new europe will mean savings of roughly 50 
million annually from among other things lower transportation 
costs product standardization and simplification of accounting 
procedures 
but reagan administration officials still voice concern about 
americans being kept out 
deputy treasury secretary peter mcpherson recently cautioned the 
eec the creation of a single market that reserves europe for 
europeans would be bad for europe for the united states and for 
the multilateral economic system 
we would find unacceptable he said in a speech in 
washington measures that would limit market access for third 
countries and discriminate against foreign companies already 
established or that wish to establish in the community 
stanley crossick senior partner of campl belmont a 
brusselsbased consulting firm that counts top us companies among 
its clients said to a major us player wellprepared and 
integrated in europe the opportunities appear to exceed the 
threats 
but he added the fortress europe question is of serious 
concern we dont want to hype it up thats a danger but it 
could be a serious issue 
a key concern analysts say is the growing use of 
reciprocity in eec discussions about how much access foreign 
companies will have in sectors such as financial services not yet 
covered by international trade rules 
de clercq said in recent speeches that the test of reciprocity 
would be used when a foreign financial institution asks permission 
to operate in an eec country 
the eec he said will check on a casebycase basis whether 
similar institutions from all member states are given the same 
treatment in the noncommunity country concerned 
if not he continued the authorization procedure will be 
suspended until we have ensured reciprocity by negotiating with the 
noncommunity country concerned 
julian oliver vice president of corporate external affairs for 
american express in london said the reciprocity issue could 
disrupt the financial markets now operating efficiently in europe 
if the community tries to do a lockout he said they risk 
cutting off their noses to spite their face foreign money he 
added could be driven out of the community to offshore banking 
centers 
us officials want the eec to apply a standard of national 
treatment to foreign firms so that us banks and other operations 
will be treated in the new market just like european companies 
us officials also are concerned the community will extend to 
all 12 countries limits that a few have on imports of certain 
products and that it will bow to protectionist demands from special 
interests in fashioning commercial and industrial policies 
this could result in new and greater discrimination in the 
areas for example of right of establishment mergers and 
acquisitions government procurement subsidies local content 
requirements and standards and certification said mcpherson 
