<TEXT>
the pentagons going to war against the 
insect repellent that troops have been using for two decades 
the old one melted plastic watch crystals and eyeglass frames 
and left an oily feeling on their skin said lt col lyman w 
roberts who helped coordinate the new version generally they 
just didnt like it 
it also smelled so bad that there was a feeling particularly 
in vietnam that an enemy could smell you if you were wearing it 
said paul klein walter reed army institute of research spokesman 
in washington 
the new repellent which looks like hand cream and comes in a 
green plastic tube will be in the hands of servicemen by next 
summer it was developed in a 43 million effort directed by the 
us army medical material development activity at fort detrick 
and was prompted in part by a 1983 survey 
fortyfive percent of the 1542 soldiers questioned seldom or 
ever used the repellent issued since the 1960s and 62 percent said 
the army needed a better one fiftyfour percent used commercial 
repellents because they smelled better felt better on their skin 
and lasted longer 
the old version was 75 percent diethyltoluamide commonly called 
deet and 25 percent alcohol roberts said the new product 35 
percent deet and with no alcohol has a milder odor it protects 
for up to 12 hours vs four hours with the old version and doesnt 
wash or wear off as easily 
the new repellent has been tested in thailand pakistan egypt 
panama honduras australia africa and alaska it protects against 
diseasecarrying arthropods such as mosquitos chiggers fleas 
biting flies deer flies and stable flies the insects can carry 
diseases such as malaria scrub typhus lyme disease dengue fever 
sand fly fever and rift valley fever 
it still will melt and cloud some cheap plastic items if you 
let it set for a while roberts said but its not as bad as 
the old product that would make a hole in the plastic 
</TEXT>
