<TEXT>
japans trade surplus fell 39 percent in august 
over a year ago and 31 percent from the previous month the finance 
ministry announced monday 
the surplus in japans international trade fell to 494 billion 
from 515 billion in august 1987 and 716 billion in july 
in july the surplus had ended a streak of 15 consecutive months 
of declines to grow by 31 percent over the previous years level 
japans trade surplus with the united states declined by 127 
percent in august over the previous year to 325 billion the 
ministry said 
looking at the overall trend the volume and value of imports 
are growing and cutting into japans surplus the government is 
also stimulating domestic demand in an attempt to curtail its 
overseas trade surplus said a finance ministry official who spoke 
on condition of anonymity 
imports surged by 273 percent on a dollar basis from the 
previous years level to a record 1586 billion for august the 
ministry said 
exports rose 182 percent in august from the previous years 
figure to 2080 billion but declined 102 percent from 2315 
billion in july 
in measuring exports officials pegged the dollar at 13313 yen 
compared with 15083 yen one year earlier and 13131 yen in july 
while imports were determined at an exchange rate of 13312 yen to 
the dollar in contrast with 15083 yen in august 1987 and 13140 
yen last month 
the ministry said japans trade surplus with the united states 
declined in part because of major hikes in imports of us food in 
august 
imports of fish soared by 1053 percent while those of meat 
rose by 996 percent the ministry reported imports of nonferrous 
metals also increased growing by 1404 percent over the previous 
year it said 
japan measures its trade on a customsclearance basis which 
includes freight and insurance costs in imports but not in exports 
if those costs were included in both categories japans trade 
surplus would be higher 
</TEXT>
