<DOCNO> AP880912-0262 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the equal employment opportunity commission 
asked a federal court monday to hold united airlines in contempt 
for failing to hire enough blacks and women as pilots 
in a motion filed in us district court in chicago the 
commission charged that united has failed to abide by a 1976 
consent decree in which the airline agreed to hire qualified 
minority and women pilots at double the rate at which they applied 
for the jobs in relation to white males 
for example according to eeoc officials if united had 100 
qualified applicants for 10 jobs and 10 of the applicants were 
women or blacks at least two of the 10 new people hired would have 
to be women or blacks under the consent decree 
based on data provided by the company the eeoc said united 
received more than 32500 applications for entrylevel pilot 
positions between 1985 and 1987 
among the 1400 pilots hired 75 were blacks or other minorities 
and 59 were women a ratio smaller than the share of blacks and 
women in the pool of applicants the commission said 
the motion also alleges that united established a selection 
criteria that was not approved by the eeoc and then used some of 
the criteria selectively to benefit white males 
we feel that some of the interviewing and evaluation standards 
were subjective and were applied subjectively said renee devine 
a spokeswoman for the commission 
joe hopkins a spokesman for united said the airline has met 
eeoc minority and women hiring targets for several categories of 
workers minorities now comprise 22 percent of uniteds total work 
force and 148 percent of its management positions he said 
however hopkins acknowledged that with the exception of june 
this year the airline has not met the consent agreements goals in 
putting women and blacks in pilot seats 
were in tremendous competition with every other major airline 
that has the same objective in trying to attract minority and 
women pilots he said theres more demand than supply 
nonetheless we are making progress and taking some steps to make 
more progress in the future 
among those steps hopkins listed recent affiliations with 
southern illinois university and delaware state college aimed 
specifically at recruiting women and blacks into uniteds pilot 
ranks and the planned development of a company scholarship program 
in addition to the contempt citation the commission is seeking 
courtordered relief that includes job offers back pay and 
retroactive seniority for as many as 3000 women and blacks who it 
says were denied employment due to discrimination 
the case dates back to 1973 when united was sued by the justice 
department on charges of employment discrimination in violation of 
the 1964 civil rights act 
</TEXT>
