general mills inc said monday it nearly 
quadrupled its first quarter net earnings compared with the same 
period last year due largely to profits on the sale of its talbots 
and eddie bauer clothing outlets 
general mills reported net income of 2899 million or 353 
per share in the three months ended aug 28 compared with net 
income of 772 million or 87 cents per share in the first 
quarter of 1987 
the 1988 figures included a 1991 million gain from 
discontinued operations the sales of talbots and eddie bauer 
completed during the first quarter generated an aftertax profit 
of 2206 million the company said 
the gain was reduced by establishment of a 215 million reserve 
for the disposition of the companys yorks cafeterias and other 
adjustments to previously discontinued operations general mills 
said it plans to dispose of yorks 100unit chain during fiscal 
1989 
firstquarter sales rose 11 percent to 138 billion from 124 
billion the company said it attributed the sales increase largely 
to a more than 5 percent volume gain in consumer foods and 
expansion of restaurants by 69 companyoperated units since the end 
of the first quarter of 1987 
aftertax earnings from continuing operations rose to 908 
million in the first quarter from firstquarter 1987 aftertax 
earnings of 809 million 
chairman hb atwater said much of the proceeds from the talbots 
and eddie bauer sales was used to repurchase common stock reducing 
average shares outstanding by 7 percent from a year earlier 
firstquarter operating highlights reflect general mills 
aggressive internal expansion programs in consumer foods and 
restaurants 
consumer foods reported gains of 9 percent in sales and 125 
percent in operating profits in the first quarter of 1988 
restaurants reported gains of 15 percent in sales and 10 percent in 
operating profits over the first quarter of last year 
